[1853.932824, "o", "\u001b[11;1Hseparator for the list of patterns, there is no way to match newline\u001b[K\u001b[12;1Hcharacters in a text.\u001b[K\u001b[12;1H\u001b[12;1H"]
[1853.964054, "o", "\u001b[12;1H\u001b[13;1H\u001b[7m-----Info: (grep)Introduction, 17 lines --Bot-------------------------------\u001b[0m\u001b[1;1HGiven one or more patterns, ‘grep’ searches input files for matches to\u001b[2;1Hthe patterns.  When it finds a match in a line, it copies the line to\u001b[K"]
[1853.964173, "o", "\u001b[3;1Hstandard output (by default), or produces whatever other sort of output\u001b[4;1Hyou have requested with options.\u001b[K\u001b[5;1H\u001b[K\u001b[6;1H   Though ‘grep’ expects to do the matching on text, it has no limits on\u001b[7;1Hinput line length other than available memory, and it can match\u001b[K\u001b[8;1Harbitrary characters within a line.  If the final byte of an input file\u001b[9;1His not a newline, ‘grep’ silently supplies one.  Since newline is also a\u001b[10;1Hseparator for the list of patterns, there is no way to match newline\u001b[K\u001b[11;1Hcharacters in a text.\u001b[K\u001b[12;1H\u001b[K\u001b[12;1H\u001b[12;1H"]
[1853.995807, "o", "\u001b[12;1H\u001b[13;1H\u001b[7m-----Info: (grep)Invoking, 22 lines --Top-----------------------------------\u001b[0m\u001b[1;1HNext: Regular Expressions,  Prev: Introduction,  Up: Top\u001b[K\u001b[2;1H\u001b[K\u001b[3;1H2 Invoking ‘grep’\u001b[K\u001b[4;1H*****************\u001b[K\u001b[6;1HThe general synopsis of the ‘grep’ command line is\u001b[K\u001b[7;1H\u001b[K\u001b[8;1H     grep [OPTION...] [PATTERNS] [FILE...]\u001b[K\u001b[9;1H\u001b[K\u001b[10;1HThere can be zero or more OPTION arguments, and zero or more FILE\u001b[K\u001b[11;1Harguments.  The PATTERNS argument contains one or more patterns\u001b[12;1Hseparated by newlines, and is omitted when patterns are given via the"]
